---
description: Avoid bash `read` loops when possible (Cursor allowlist friendliness)
alwaysApply: true
globs:
  - "**/*.ts"
  - "**/*.tsx"
  - "**/*.js"
  - "**/*.jsx"
  - "**/*.mjs"
  - "**/*.cjs"
---

## Rule

Avoid bash `read` usage (especially `while read -r ...; do ...`) when an alternative is practical.

## Why

In this repository/workflow, Cursor can block allowlisting on commands that include `read` with parameters.
This can stall unattended work even for read-only operations.

## Preferred alternatives (choose the simplest)

- **Python heredoc** (preferred for small parsing/transforms):
  - `python3 - <<'PY' ... PY`
- **Single-purpose tools** without shell loops:
  - `grep`, `sed`, `awk`, `find`, `xargs` (bounded with `head -n <N>`)
- **Multiple explicit commands** instead of a loop when the list is short (≤10 items).

## Notes

- Keep outputs bounded (`head`, `tail`) to avoid tool timeouts.
- This rule is about command-shape robustness; it does not change the existing refactoring guardrails.
